### Prelude

Before we begin the discussion, I would like to point out that the explicit call to `super()` in `Child`&#39;s constructor is superfluous and added implicitly if we remove it (see [JLS, &#167;8.8.7][JLS]). So we can simplify `Child` to:

    class Child extends Parent {
        private int i;

        public Child(int i) {
            this.i = i;
        }

        @Override
        public void print() {
            System.out.println(&quot;This code doesn&#39;t work, i = &quot; + i); // i is not initalized
        }
    }

This is to show that this problem may even hit programmers who do not know of the implicit `super()` call and/or do not use `super()`.

---
### The actual question

We cannot prevent such behaviour. There is only a rule we can follow: [Do not leak premature objects][prematureObjects]. A consequence of this rule is that we should only call private or final methods from constructors. In the code presented, we violate this rule. This allows us to &quot;break&quot; the code even more by declaring field `private int i` in class `Child` as `final`:
    
    class Child extends Parent {
      private final int i;

      public Child(int i) {
        this.i = i;
      }
    
      @Override
      public void print() {
        System.out.println(&quot;This code doesn&#39;t work, i = &quot; + i); // i is not initalized
      }
    }

[&lt;kbd&gt;Ideone demo&lt;/kbd&gt;][Ideone]

We would expect that `i` has one and only one value, but we clearly see that `i` changes its value.

---
### Remark
In the original code, the field `i` is (always) initialized. This stems from the fact that non-final fields, other than local variables, are always initialized with a default value (primitives with `0` or `false`, reference types with `null`).

[JLS]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se16/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.8.7

[prematureObjects]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18107128/what-is-happens-before-relations-in-synchronization-what-is-premature-object-le

[Ideone]: https://ideone.com/XFwjnO

